node.text: British 18-year-old Emma Raducanu won the first all-teen US Open final since 1999 by defeating Canadian Leylah Fernandez 6-4, 6-3.  With her straight-set victory, Raducanu did not drop a set in the entire tournament. She had to go through three rounds of qualifying to even make the main draw for what is only her second grand slam appearance. Raducanu is the first qualifier to win a grand slam final. A historic win 🙌. (📸 : Elsa/Getty Images, Al Bello/Getty Images)

node.text:
Former President George W. Bush made an appeal for unity and honored 9/11 victims during the remembrance ceremony at the Flight 93 memorial in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.

“There was horror at the scale of destruction and awe at the bravery and kindness that rose to meet it. There was shock at the audacity of evil and gratitude for the heroism and decency that opposed it,” Bush said. “In the sacrifice of the first responders and the mutual aid of strangers, in the solidarity of grief and grace, the actions of an enemy revealed the spirit of a people. We were proud of our wounded nation.”

(Mandel Ngan/AFP via Getty Images)

node.text: Jeremy Booth was just coming into his finance job in San Francisco when the Twin Towers were struck. Watching coverage of the rescue efforts, he saw the FDNY’s heroic response and knew that was his calling. After years of training, he is now a captain with the Richmond Fire Department in California.

node.text: September 11, 2001, was a wake-up call, said Sadia Sheikh, who moved to the US from Pakistan in 1978. When she turned on the TV that morning, what she saw on the screen hit her hard. At that moment, as a Muslim American, she said she knew her life would never be the same again.

node.text: “Most people say, ‘Oh, you were part of 9/11.’ I just tell them, ‘You know what, 9/11 is part of me,’” said Tom Canavan. He was buried when the South Tower came down and dug his way free. He was one of the fewer than two dozen to survive the collapse.
